Vice President Mike Pence visited NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Alabama, where he expressed his gratitude and admiration for the astronauts aboard the International Space Station (ISS). He also invited them to the White House upon their return to Earth. Pence toured the Space Flight Center, including the testing facility of the Space Launch System (SLS), the largest and most powerful rocket on Earth. He received updates on the progress of the SLS and International Space Station science operations. Pence also visited the Payload Operations Integration Center (POIC), where ground controllers support the crew's scientific activities. After the visit, Pence announced that the first meeting of the National Space Council is scheduled to occur on October 5th at the Steven F. Udvar-Hazy Center in Virginia. The meeting will bring together experts from the Civil, Commercial, and National Security Space industries to discuss the future of space exploration.